# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: august-bank-holiday
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] Common examples include ad hoc committees and commissions created at the national or international level for a specific task, and the term is often used to describe arbitration (ad hoc arbitration).
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] Ad hoc can also function as an adjective describing temporary, provisional, or improvised methods to deal with a particular problem, the tendency of which has given rise to the noun *adhocism*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] This concept highlights the flexibility and adaptability often required in problem-solving across various domains.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] In everyday language, "ad hoc" is sometimes used informally to describe improvised or makeshift solutions, emphasizing their temporary nature and specific applicability to immediate circumstances.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] Style guides disagree on whether Latin phrases like ad hoc should be italicized.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] For example, *The Chicago Manual of Style* recommends that familiar Latin phrases that are listed in the *Webster's Dictionary*, including "ad hoc", not be italicized.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] In science and philosophy, ad hoc means the addition of extraneous hypotheses to a theory to save it from being falsified.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] Ad hoc hypotheses compensate for anomalies not anticipated by the theory in its unmodified form.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] Scientists are often skeptical of scientific theories that rely on frequent, unsupported adjustments to sustain them.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] Ad hoc hypotheses are often characteristic of pseudo-scientific subjects such as homeopathy.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] In the military, ad hoc units are created during unpredictable situations, when the cooperation between different units is suddenly needed for fast action, or from remnants of previous units which have been overrun or otherwise whittled down.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] In national and sub-national governance, ad hoc bodies may be established to deal with specific problems not easily accommodated by the current structure of governance or to address multi-faceted issues spanning several areas of governance.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] In the UK and other commonwealth countries, ad hoc Royal Commissions may be set up to address specific questions as directed by parliament.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] In diplomacy, diplomats may be appointed by a government as special envoys, or diplomats who serve on an ad hoc basis due to the possibility that such envoys' offices may either not be retained by a future government or may only exist during the duration of a relevant cause.
[src:august-bank-holiday/ad-hoc] The term *ad hoc networking* typically refers to a system of network elements that combine to form a network requiring little or no planning.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Adherents of Anglicanism are called *Anglicans*; they are also called *Episcopalians* in some countries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Most are members of national or regional ecclesiastical provinces of the international Anglican Communion, one of the largest Christian bodies in the world, and the world's third-largest Christian communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The provinces within the Anglican Communion have historically been in full communion with the See of Canterbury and thus with the archbishop of Canterbury, whom the communion refers to as its *primus inter pares* (Latin, 'first among equals').
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The archbishop calls the decennial Lambeth Conference, chairs the meeting of primates, and is the president of the Anglican Consultative Council.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Some churches that are not part of the Anglican Communion or recognised by it also call themselves Anglican, including those that are within the Continuing Anglican movement and Anglican realignment.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicans base their Christian faith on the Bible, traditions of the apostolic church, apostolic succession ("historic episcopate"), and the writings of the Church Fathers, as well as, historically, the *Thirty-nine Articles* and *The Books of Homilies*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicanism forms a branch of Western Christianity, having declared its independence from the Holy See through the Act of Supremacy in 1534, a separation later consolidated by the Elizabethan Religious Settlement.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Many of the Anglican formularies of the mid-16th century correspond closely to those of historical Protestantism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The degree of distinction between Protestant and Catholic tendencies within Anglicanism is routinely a matter of debate both within specific Anglican churches and the Anglican Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The *Book of Common Prayer* is unique to Anglicanism, the collection of services in one prayer book used for centuries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The book is acknowledged as a principal tie that binds the Anglican Communion as a liturgical tradition.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Through the expansion of the British Empire and the activity of Christian missions, this model was adopted as the model for many newly formed churches, especially in Africa, Australasia, and the Asia-Pacific.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In the late-19th century, the term *Anglicanism* was coined to describe the common religious tradition of these churches and also that of the Scottish Episcopal Church, which, though originating earlier within the Church of Scotland, had come to be recognised as sharing this common identity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] By the 21st century, the global centre of Anglicanism had shifted to the Global South, particularly sub-Saharan Africa, with 63,556,000 in Africa, 24,400,000 in Europe, 4,565,000 in Oceania, 2,689,000 in Northern America, 1,230,000 in Asia, and 959,000 in Latin America in 2020.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The word *Anglican* originates in *ecclesia anglicana*, a medieval Latin phrase that means the *English Church*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Adherents of Anglicanism are called *Anglicans*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] As an adjective, *Anglican* is used to describe the people, institutions, churches, liturgical traditions, and theological concepts developed by the Church of England.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] As a noun, an Anglican is a church member in the Anglican Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The word is also used by followers of separated groups that have left the communion or have been founded separately from it.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The word originally referred only to the teachings and rites of Christians throughout the world in communion with the see of Canterbury but has come to sometimes be extended to any church following those traditions or rites rather than actual membership in the Anglican Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Although the term *Anglican* is found referring to the Church of England as far back as the 16th century, its use did not become general until the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In British parliamentary legislation referring to the English Established Church, there is no need for a description; it is simply the Church of England, though the word *Protestant* is used in many legal acts specifying the succession to the Crown and qualifications for office.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] When the Union with Ireland Act created the United Church of England and Ireland, it is specified that it shall be one "Protestant Episcopal Church", thereby distinguishing its form of church government from the Presbyterian polity that prevails in the Church of Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Elsewhere, however, the term *Anglican Church* came to be preferred as it distinguished these churches from others that maintain an episcopal polity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicans understand the Old and New Testaments as "containing all things necessary for salvation" and as being the rule and ultimate standard of faith.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Reason and tradition are seen as valuable means to interpret scripture (a position first formulated in detail by Richard Hooker), but there is no full mutual agreement among Anglicans about *exactly how* scripture, reason, and tradition interact (or ought to interact) with each other.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicans understand the Apostles' Creed as the baptismal symbol and the Nicene Creed as the sufficient statement of the Christian faith.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicans believe the catholic and apostolic faith is revealed in Holy Scripture and the ecumenical creeds (Apostles', Nicene and Athanasian) and interpret these in light of the Christian tradition of the historic church, scholarship, reason, and experience.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicans celebrate the traditional sacraments, with special emphasis being given to the Eucharist, also called Holy Communion, the Lord's Supper, or the Mass.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The consecrated bread and wine are considered by Anglican formularies to be the true body and blood of Christ received in a spiritual manner.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The sacrament is understood as being an outward and visible sign of an inward and spiritual grace given by Christ which conveys forgiveness and cleansing from sin.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] While many Anglicans celebrate the Eucharist in ways similar to the predominant Latin Catholic tradition, a considerable degree of liturgical freedom is permitted and worship styles range from simple to elaborate.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Unique to Anglicanism is the *Book of Common Prayer* (BCP), the collection of services which worshippers in most Anglican churches have used for centuries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] It was called *common prayer* originally because it was intended for use in all Church of England churches, which had previously followed differing local liturgies.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The term was kept when the church became international because all Anglicans used to share in its use around the world.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In 1549, the first *Book of Common Prayer* was compiled by Thomas Cranmer, the then archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] While it has since undergone many revisions and Anglican churches in different countries have developed other service books, the BCP is still acknowledged as one of the ties that bind Anglicans together.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] According to legend, the founding of Christianity in Britain is commonly attributed to Joseph of Arimathea and is commemorated at Glastonbury Abbey.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Many of the early Church Fathers wrote of the presence of Christianity in Roman Britain, with Tertullian stating "those parts of Britain into which the Roman arms had never penetrated were become subject to Christ".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Saint Alban, who was executed in AD 209, is the first Christian martyr in the British Isles.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] For this reason he is venerated as the British protomartyr.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] After Roman troops withdrew from Britain, the "absence of Roman military and governmental influence and overall decline of Roman imperial political power enabled Britain and the surrounding isles to develop distinctively from the rest of the West.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] A new culture emerged around the Irish Sea among the Celtic peoples with Celtic Christianity at its core.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In what is known as the Gregorian mission, Pope Gregory I sent Augustine of Canterbury to the British Isles in AD 596, with the purpose of evangelising the pagans there (who were largely Anglo-Saxons), as well as to reconcile the Celtic churches in the British Isles to the See of Rome.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In Kent, Augustine persuaded the Anglo-Saxon king "Æthelberht and his people to accept Christianity".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Augustine, on two occasions, "met in conference with members of the Celtic episcopacy, but no understanding was reached between them".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Eventually, the "Christian Church of the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Northumbria convened the Synod of Whitby in 663/664 to decide whether to follow Celtic or Roman usages".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] This meeting, with King Oswiu as the final decision maker, "led to the acceptance of Roman usage elsewhere in England and brought the English Church into close contact with the Continent".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] As a result of assuming Roman usages, the Celtic Church surrendered its independence, and, from this point on, the Church in England "was no longer purely Celtic, but became Anglo-Roman-Celtic".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Following the Synod of Whitby, tensions between Rome and the English king would gradually escalate, due in part to royal assertions that it was the custom of England for the king to exercise authority over the Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In the late 1000s, William the Conqueror (William I) refused to swear fealty to the Pope citing English tradition, controlled appointments to ecclesiastical offices (a power historically reserved to the Pope) and forbade papal legates to enter England without royal permission.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In 1164, under Henry II, the Constitutions of Clarendon, citing English custom, required royal assent for excommunications and mandated that ecclesiastical court appeals terminate with the king rather than the Pope.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The Magna Carta in 1215, asserting that "the English Church shall be free, and shall have its rights undiminished, and its liberties unimpaired" would be annulled by Pope Innocent III, but reissued in both 1216 and 1225.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Under Edward I, in 1279, the Statute of Mortmain required royal approval to grant or transfer land to the Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Additionally, Edward I would reject Pope Boniface VIII's bull *Clericis Laicos* which forbade secular taxation of clergy.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Per the king's orders, non-compliant clergy were punished by law and church property was seized.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The 1351 Statute of Provisors, under Edward III, prohibited papal appointments to English benefices, reserving the power for the king.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The 1353 Statute of Praemunire prohibited appeals to papal courts for either ecclesiastical or temporal matters.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] To date, neither the Statute of Provisors nor the Statute of Praemunire has been repealed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In 1401, Henry IV's statute *De Heretico Comburendo* would transfer heresy trials from ecclesiastical to secular courts, further cementing the tradition of English kings claiming authority over English ecclesiastical matters.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] English delegates to the Councils of Pisa (1409), Constance (1414–1418), and Basel (1431–1445) would voice support for conciliarism in an attempt to limit the powers of the Pope over-against the bishops of the Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The Church in England remained united with Rome until the English Parliament passed the Act of Supremacy in 1534, declaring King Henry VIII the "Supreme Head" of the Church of England.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] This act culminated centuries of English monarchs asserting authority over ecclesiastical matters, from William I's refusal of papal fealty (1070s) to the Statutes of Provisors (1351) and Praemunire (1353).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Henry and his theologians, including Thomas Cranmer, cited these historical customs to justify royal supremacy, arguing that the crown traditionally governed the Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The immediate catalyst was Henry's need to annul his 24-year marriage to Catherine of Aragon, which he believed was invalid based on biblical prohibitions (Leviticus 20:21) and the lack of a male heir, seen as divine judgment.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] When Pope Clement VII, under pressure from Emperor Charles V, refused the annulment, Henry acted to resolve the issue domestically, supported by legislative steps like the Submission of the Clergy (1534) and Act in Restraint of Appeals (1533).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The break with Rome reflected a mix of theological conviction, historical precedent, and political necessity, fulfilling a longstanding English desire for ecclesiastical autonomy while addressing immediate dynastic concerns.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] This laid the foundation for the development of Anglicanism as a distinct national church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The English Church under Henry VIII continued to maintain Catholic doctrines and liturgical celebrations of the sacraments despite its separation from Rome.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] With little exception, Henry VIII allowed no changes during his lifetime.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Under King Edward VI (1547–1553), however, the church in England first began to undergo what is known as the English Reformation, in the course of which it acquired a number of characteristics that would subsequently become recognised as constituting its distinctive "Anglican" identity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] With the Elizabethan Settlement of 1559, the Protestant identity of the English and Irish churches was affirmed by means of parliamentary legislation which mandated allegiance and loyalty to the English Crown in all their members.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Over the years, these traditions came to command adherence and loyalty.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The Elizabethan Settlement stopped the radical Protestant tendencies under Edward VI by combining the more radical elements of the 1552 prayer book with the conservative "Catholic" 1549 prayer book into the 1559 *Book of Common Prayer*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] From then on, Protestantism was in a "state of arrested development", regardless of the attempts to detach the Church of England from its "idiosyncratic anchorage in the medieval past" by various groups which tried to push it towards a more Reformed theology and governance in the years 1560–1660.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Neither does the term *via media* appear until the 1627 to describe a church which refused to identify itself definitely as Catholic or Protestant, or as both, "and had decided in the end that this is virtue rather than a handicap".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Since the late 1960s, these interpretations have been criticised.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Studies on the subject written during the last forty-five years have, however, not reached any consensus on how to interpret this period in English church history.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In 1662, under King Charles II, a revised *Book of Common Prayer* was produced, which was acceptable to high churchmen as well as some Puritans and is still considered authoritative to this day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] For these American patriots, even the forms of Anglican services were in doubt, since the Prayer Book rites of Matins, Evensong, and Holy Communion all included specific prayers for the British royal family.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Reluctantly, legislation was passed in the British Parliament (the Consecration of Bishops Abroad Act 1786) to allow bishops to be consecrated for an American church outside of allegiance to the British Crown (since no dioceses had ever been established in the former American colonies).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Both in the United States and in Canada, the new Anglican churches developed novel models of self-government, collective decision-making, and self-supported financing; that would be consistent with separation of religious and secular identities.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In the following century, two further factors acted to accelerate the development of a distinct Anglican identity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The propriety of this legislation was bitterly contested by the Oxford Movement (Tractarians), who in response developed a vision of Anglicanism as religious tradition deriving ultimately from the ecumenical councils of the patristic church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Those within the Church of England opposed to the Tractarians, and to their revived ritual practices, introduced a stream of bills in parliament aimed to control innovations in worship.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] This only made the dilemma more acute, with consequent continual litigation in the secular and ecclesiastical courts.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Over the same period, Anglican churches engaged vigorously in Christian missions, resulting in the creation, by the end of the century, of over ninety colonial bishoprics, which gradually coalesced into new self-governing churches on the Canadian and American models.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Consequently, at the instigation of the bishops of Canada and South Africa, the first Lambeth Conference was called in 1867; to be followed by further conferences in 1878 and 1888, and thereafter at ten-year intervals.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The various papers and declarations of successive Lambeth Conferences have served to frame the continued Anglican debate on identity, especially as relating to the possibility of ecumenical discussion with other churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Anglicanism was seen as a middle way, or *via media*, between two branches of Protestantism, Lutheranism and Reformed Christianity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] In their rejection of absolute parliamentary authority, the Tractarians, especially John Henry Newman, looked back to the writings of 17th-century Anglican divines, finding in these texts the idea of the English church as a *via media* between the Protestant and Catholic traditions.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] This view was associated – especially in the writings of Edward Bouverie Pusey – with the theory of Anglicanism as one of three "branches" (alongside the Catholic Church and the Orthodox Churches) historically arising out of the common tradition of the earliest ecumenical councils.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Newman himself subsequently rejected his theory of the *via media*, as essentially historicist and static and hence unable to accommodate any dynamic development within the church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Nevertheless, the aspiration to ground Anglican identity in the writings of the 17th-century divines and in faithfulness to the traditions of the Church Fathers reflects a continuing theme of Anglican ecclesiology, most recently in the writings of Henry Robert McAdoo.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] The Tractarian formulation of the theory of the *via media* between Protestantism and Catholicism was essentially a party platform, and not acceptable to Anglicans outside the confines of the Oxford Movement.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] However, this theory of the via media was reworked in the ecclesiological writings of Frederick Denison Maurice, in a more dynamic form that became widely influential.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Both Maurice and Newman saw the Church of England of their day as sorely deficient in faith; but whereas Newman had looked back to a distant past when the light of faith might have appeared to burn brighter, Maurice looked forward to the possibility of a brighter revelation of faith in the future.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Maurice saw the Protestant and Catholic strands within the Church of England as contrary but complementary, both maintaining elements of the true church, but incomplete without the other; such that a true catholic and evangelical church might come into being by a union of opposites.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Central to Maurice's perspective was his belief that the collective elements of family, nation, and church represented a divine order of structures through which God unfolds his continuing work of creation.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Hence, for Maurice, the Protestant tradition had maintained the elements of national distinction which were amongst the marks of the true universal church, but which had been lost within contemporary Catholicism in the internationalism of centralised papal authority.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] This vision of a becoming universal church as a congregation of autonomous national churches proved highly congenial in Anglican circles; and Maurice's six signs were adapted to form the Chicago-Lambeth Quadrilateral of 1888.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Hence, the Catholic Church does not regard itself as a party or strand within the universal church – but rather identifies itself as the universal church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Moreover, Sykes criticises the proposition, implicit in theories of *via media*, that there is no distinctive body of Anglican doctrines, other than those of the universal church; accusing this of being an excuse not to undertake systematic doctrine at all.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p01] Contrariwise, Sykes notes a high degree of commonality in Anglican liturgical forms and in the doctrinal understandings expressed within those liturgies.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The distinction between Reformed and Catholic, and the coherence of the two, is a matter of debate within the Anglican Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Oxford Movement of the mid-19th century revived and extended doctrinal, liturgical, and pastoral practices similar to those of Roman Catholicism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This extends beyond the ceremony of high church services to even more theologically significant territory, such as sacramental theology (see Anglican sacraments).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] While Anglo-Catholic practices, particularly liturgical ones, have become more common within the tradition over the last century, there are also places where practices and beliefs resonate more closely with the evangelical movements of the 1730s (see Sydney Anglicanism).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] For high-church Anglicans, doctrine is neither established by a magisterium, nor derived from the theology of an eponymous founder (such as Calvinism), nor summed up in a confession of faith beyond the ecumenical creeds, such as the Lutheran Book of Concord.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] For them, the earliest Anglican theological documents are its prayer books, which they see as the products of profound theological reflection, compromise, and synthesis.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] They emphasise the *Book of Common Prayer* as a key expression of Anglican doctrine.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The principle of looking to the prayer books as a guide to the parameters of belief and practice is called by the Latin name *lex orandi, lex credendi* ("the law of prayer is the law of belief").
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Within the prayer books are the fundamentals of Anglican doctrine: the Apostles' and Nicene creeds, the Athanasian Creed (now rarely used), the scriptures (via the lectionary), the sacraments, daily prayer, the catechism, and apostolic succession in the context of the historic threefold ministry.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] For some low-church and evangelical Anglicans, the 16th-century Reformed Thirty-Nine Articles form the basis of doctrine.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Thirty-Nine Articles played a significant role in Anglican doctrine and practice.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Following the passing of the 1604 canons, all Anglican clergy had to formally subscribe to the articles.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Today, however, the articles are no longer binding, but are seen as a historical document which has played a significant role in the shaping of Anglican identity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The degree to which each of the articles has remained influential varies.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] On the doctrine of justification, for example, there is a wide range of beliefs within the Anglican Communion, with some Anglo-Catholics arguing for a faith with good works and the sacraments.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] At the same time, however, some evangelical Anglicans ascribe to the Reformed emphasis on *sola fide* ("faith alone") in their doctrine of justification (see Sydney Anglicanism).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Still other Anglicans adopt a nuanced view of justification, taking elements from the early Church Fathers, Catholicism, Protestantism, liberal theology, and latitudinarian thought.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglicans look for authority in their "standard divines" (see below).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Historically, the most influential of these – apart from Cranmer – has been the 16th-century cleric and theologian Richard Hooker, who after 1660 was increasingly portrayed as the founding father of Anglicanism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The analogy of the "three-legged stool" of scripture, reason, and tradition is often incorrectly attributed to Hooker.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Rather, Hooker's description is a hierarchy of authority, with scripture as foundational and reason and tradition as vitally important, but secondary, authorities.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Finally, the extension of Anglicanism into non-English cultures, the growing diversity of prayer books, and the increasing interest in ecumenical dialogue have led to further reflection on the parameters of Anglican identity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Many Anglicans look to the Chicago-Lambeth Quadrilateral of 1888 as the *sine qua non* of communal identity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Within the Anglican tradition, "divines" are clergy of the Church of England whose theological writings have been considered standards for faith, doctrine, worship, and spirituality, and whose influence has permeated the Anglican Communion in varying degrees through the years.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] While there is no authoritative list of these Anglican divines, there are some whose names would likely be found on most lists – those who are commemorated in lesser feasts of the Anglican churches and those whose works are frequently anthologised.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The corpus produced by Anglican divines is diverse.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] What they have in common is a commitment to the faith as conveyed by scripture and the *Book of Common Prayer*, thus regarding prayer and theology in a manner akin to that of the Apostolic Fathers.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] On the whole, Anglican divines view the *via media* of Anglicanism not as a compromise, but as "a positive position, witnessing to the universality of God and God's kingdom working through the fallible, earthly *ecclesia Anglicana*".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] These theologians regard scripture as interpreted through tradition and reason as authoritative in matters concerning salvation.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Reason and tradition, indeed, are extant in and presupposed by scripture, thus implying co-operation between God and humanity, God and nature, and between the sacred and secular.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Faith is thus regarded as incarnational and authority as dispersed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Amongst the early Anglican divines of the 16th and 17th centuries, the names of Thomas Cranmer, John Jewel, Matthew Parker, Richard Hooker, Lancelot Andrewes, and Jeremy Taylor predominate.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The influential character of Hooker's *Of the Laws of Ecclesiastical Polity* cannot be overestimated.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Published in 1593 and subsequently, Hooker's eight-volume work is primarily a treatise on church-state relations, but it deals comprehensively with issues of biblical interpretation, soteriology, ethics, and sanctification.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Throughout the work, Hooker makes clear that theology involves prayer and is concerned with ultimate issues and that theology is relevant to the social mission of the church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The 17th century saw the rise of two important movements in Anglicanism: Cambridge Platonism, with its mystical understanding of reason as the "candle of the Lord", and the Evangelical Revival, with its emphasis on the personal experience of the Holy Spirit.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Cambridge Platonist movement evolved into a school called Latitudinarianism, which emphasised reason as the barometer of discernment and took a stance of indifference towards doctrinal and ecclesiological differences.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Evangelical Revival, influenced by such figures as John Wesley and Charles Simeon, re-emphasised the importance of justification through faith and the consequent importance of personal conversion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Some in this movement, such as Wesley and George Whitefield, took the message to the United States, influencing the First Great Awakening and creating an Anglo-American movement called Methodism that would eventually break away, structurally, from the Anglican churches after the American Revolution.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] By the 19th century, there was a renewed interest in pre-Reformation English religious thought and practice.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Their work is largely credited with the development of the Oxford Movement, which sought to reassert Catholic identity and practice in Anglicanism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In contrast to this movement, clergy such as the Bishop of Liverpool, J.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Ryle, sought to uphold the distinctly Reformed identity of the Church of England.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] He was not a servant of the status quo, but argued for a lively religion which emphasised grace, holy and charitable living, and the plain use of the 1662 *Book of Common Prayer* (interpreted in a partisan evangelical way) without additional rituals.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Frederick Denison Maurice, through such works as *The Kingdom of Christ*, played a pivotal role in inaugurating another movement, Christian socialism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In this, Maurice transformed Hooker's emphasis on the incarnational nature of Anglican spirituality to an imperative for social justice.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the 19th century, Anglican biblical scholarship began to assume a distinct character, represented by the so-called "Cambridge triumvirate" of Joseph Lightfoot, F.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Resistance to the growing acceptance and restoration of traditional Catholic ceremonial by the mainstream of Anglicanism ultimately led to the formation of small breakaway churches such as the Free Church of England in England (1844) and the Reformed Episcopal Church in North America (1873).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglo-Catholic (and some broad-church) Anglicans celebrate public liturgy in ways that understand worship to be something very special and of utmost importance.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Vestments are worn by the clergy, sung settings are often used, and incense may be used.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Nowadays, in most Anglican churches, the Eucharist is celebrated in a manner similar to the usage of Roman Catholics and some Lutherans, though, in many churches, more traditional, "pre–Vatican II" models of worship are common (e.g., an "eastward orientation" at the altar).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Whilst many Anglo-Catholics derive much of their liturgical practice from that of the pre-Reformation English church, others more closely follow traditional Roman Catholic practices.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Eucharist may sometimes be celebrated in the form known as High Mass, with a priest, deacon and subdeacon (usually actually a layman) dressed in traditional vestments, with incense and sanctus bells and prayers adapted from the Roman Missal or other sources by the celebrant.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Such churches may also have forms of eucharistic adoration such as Benediction of the Blessed Sacrament.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In terms of personal piety, some Anglicans may recite the Rosary and Angelus, be involved in a devotional society dedicated to "Our Lady" (the Blessed Virgin Mary) and seek the intercession of the saints.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] For their part, those evangelical (and some broad-church) Anglicans who emphasise the more Protestant aspects of the Church stress the Reformation theme of salvation by grace through faith.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] They emphasise the two dominical sacraments of Baptism and Eucharist, viewing the other five as "lesser rites".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Some evangelical Anglicans may even tend to take the inerrancy of scripture literally, adopting the view of Article VI that it contains all things necessary to salvation in an explicit sense.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Worship in churches influenced by these principles tends to be significantly less elaborate, with greater emphasis on the Liturgy of the Word (the reading of the scriptures, the sermon, and the intercessory prayers).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Order for Holy Communion may be celebrated bi-weekly or monthly (in preference to the daily offices), by priests attired in choir habit, or more regular clothes, rather than Eucharistic vestments.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the early 21st century, there has been a growth of charismatic worship among Anglicans.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Both Anglo-Catholics and evangelicals have been affected by this movement such that it is not uncommon to find typically charismatic postures, music, and other themes evident during the services of otherwise Anglo-Catholic or evangelical parishes.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The spectrum of Anglican beliefs and practice is too large to be fit into these labels.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Many Anglicans locate themselves somewhere in the spectrum of the broad-church tradition and consider themselves an amalgam of evangelical and Catholic.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Such Anglicans stress that Anglicanism is the *via media* (middle way) between the two major strains of Western Christianity and that Anglicanism is like a "bridge" between the two strains.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In accord with its prevailing self-identity as a *via media* or "middle path" of Western Christianity, Anglican sacramental theology expresses elements in keeping with its status as being both a church in the Catholic tradition as well as a Reformed church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] With respect to sacramental theology, the Catholic heritage is perhaps most strongly asserted in the importance Anglicanism places on the sacraments as a means of grace, sanctification, and salvation, as expressed in the church's liturgy and doctrine.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Of the seven sacraments, all Anglicans recognise Baptism and the Eucharist as being directly instituted by Christ.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The Thirty-Nine Articles say that there are only two sacraments.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglican eucharistic theology is divergent in practice, reflecting the essential comprehensiveness of the tradition.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] A few low-church Anglicans take a strictly memorialist (Zwinglian) view of the sacrament.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In other words, they see Holy Communion as a memorial to Christ's suffering, and participation in the Eucharist as both a re-enactment of the Last Supper and a foreshadowing of the heavenly banquet – the fulfilment of the eucharistic promise.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Other low-church Anglicans believe in the real presence of Christ in the Eucharist but deny that the presence of Christ is carnal or is necessarily localised in the bread and wine.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The majority of Anglicans, however, have in common a belief in the real presence, defined in one way or another.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] To that extent, they are in the company of the continental reformer Martin Luther and Calvin rather than Ulrich Zwingli.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] It should be remembered that Anglicanism has no official doctrine on this matter, believing it is wiser to leave the Presence a mystery.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] An Anglican position on the eucharistic sacrifice ("Sacrifice of the Mass") was expressed in the response *Saepius officio* of the archbishops of Canterbury and York to Pope Leo XIII's papal encyclical *Apostolicae curae*: viz. that the Prayer Book contained a strong sacrificial theology.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglican and Roman Catholic representatives declared that they had "substantial agreement on the doctrine of the Eucharist" in the *Windsor Statement on Eucharistic Doctrine* by the Anglican-Roman Catholic International Consultation (1971) and the Elucidation of the ARCIC Windsor Statement (1979).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The final response (1991) to these documents by the Vatican made it plain that it did not consider the degree of agreement reached to be satisfactory.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In Anglicanism there is a distinction between liturgy, which is the formal public and communal worship of the church, and personal prayer and devotion, which may be public or private.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Liturgy is regulated by the prayer books and consists of the Eucharist (some call it Holy Communion or Mass), the other six sacraments, and the daily offices such as Morning Prayer and Evening Prayer.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The *Book of Common Prayer* (BCP) is the foundational prayer book of Anglicanism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Suppressed under Queen Mary I, it was revised in 1559, and then again in 1662, after the Restoration of Charles II.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This version was made mandatory in England and Wales by the Act of Uniformity and was in standard use until the mid-20th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] With British colonial expansion from the 17th century onwards, Anglican churches were planted around the globe.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglican worship services are open to all visitors.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglican worship originates principally in the reforms of Thomas Cranmer, who aimed to create a set order of service like that of the pre-Reformation church but less complex in its seasonal variety and said in English rather than Latin.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This use of a set order of service is not unlike the Catholic tradition.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Traditionally, the pattern was that laid out in the *Book of Common Prayer*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Although many Anglican churches now use a wide range of modern service books written in the local language, the structures of the *Book of Common Prayer* are largely retained.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Churches which call themselves Anglican will have identified themselves so because they use some form or variant of the *Book of Common Prayer* in the shaping of their worship.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglican worship, however, is as diverse as Anglican theology.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] A contemporary "low church" service may differ little from the worship of many mainstream non-Anglican Protestant churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The service is constructed around a sermon focused on Biblical exposition and opened with one or more Bible readings and closed by a series of prayers (both set and extemporised) and hymns or songs.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] A "high church" or Anglo-Catholic service, by contrast, is usually a more formal liturgy celebrated by clergy in distinctive vestments and may be almost indistinguishable from a Roman Catholic service, often resembling the "pre–Vatican II" Tridentine rite.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Between these extremes are a variety of styles of worship, often involving a robed choir and the use of the organ to accompany the singing and to provide music before and after the service.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglican churches tend to have pews or chairs, and it is usual for the congregation to kneel for some prayers but to stand for hymns and other parts of the service such as the Gloria, Collect, Gospel reading, Creed and either the Preface or all of the Eucharistic Prayer.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglicans may genuflect or cross themselves in the same way as Roman Catholics.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Other more traditional Anglicans tend to follow the 1662 *Book of Common Prayer* and retain the use of the King James Bible.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This is typical in many Anglican cathedrals and particularly in royal peculiars such as the Savoy Chapel and the Queen's Chapel.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] These Anglican church services include classical music instead of songs, hymns from the New English Hymnal (usually excluding modern hymns such as "Lord of the Dance"), and are generally non-evangelical and formal in practice.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Until the mid-20th century the main Sunday service was typically Morning Prayer, but the Eucharist has once again become the standard form of Sunday worship in most Anglican churches; this again is similar to Roman Catholic practice.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Other common Sunday services include an early morning Eucharist without music, an abbreviated Eucharist following a service of morning prayer, and a service of Evening Prayer, often called "Evensong" when sung, usually celebrated between 3:00 and 6:00 pm.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The late-evening service of Compline was revived in parish use in the early 20th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Many Anglican churches will also have daily morning and evening prayer, and some have midweek or even daily celebration of the Eucharist.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The sermon (or homily) is typically about ten to twenty minutes in length, often comparably short to sermons in evangelical churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Even in the most informal Anglican services, it is common for set prayers such as the weekly Collect to be read.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] There are also set forms for intercessory prayer, though this is now more often extemporaneous.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In high and Anglo-Catholic churches there are generally prayers for the dead.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Although Anglican public worship is usually ordered according to the canonically approved services, in practice many Anglican churches use forms of service outside these norms.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Liberal churches may use freely structured or experimental forms of worship, including patterns borrowed from ecumenical traditions such as those of the Taizé Community or the Iona Community.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Anglo-Catholic parishes might use the modern Roman Catholic liturgy of the Mass or more traditional forms, such as the Tridentine Mass (which is translated into English in the English Missal), the Anglican Missal, or, less commonly, the Sarum Rite.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Catholic devotions such as the Rosary, Angelus, and Benediction of the Blessed Sacrament are also common among Anglo-Catholics.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Only baptised persons are eligible to receive communion, although in many churches communion is restricted to those who have not only been baptised but also confirmed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In many Anglican provinces, however, all baptised Christians are now often invited to receive communion and some dioceses have regularised a system for admitting baptised young people to communion before they are confirmed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The discipline of fasting before communion is practised by some Anglicans.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] As in the Roman Catholic Church, it is a canonical requirement to use fermented wine for communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Unlike in Roman Catholicism, the consecrated bread and wine are normally offered to the congregation at a eucharistic service ("communion in both kinds").
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This practice is becoming more frequent in the Roman Catholic Church as well, especially through the Neocatechumenal Way.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In some churches, the sacrament is reserved in a tabernacle or aumbry with a lighted candle or lamp nearby.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In Anglican churches, only a priest or a bishop may be the celebrant at the Eucharist.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] All Anglican prayer books contain offices for Morning Prayer and Evening Prayer (called Evensong when sung chorally).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the original *Book of Common Prayer*, these were derived from combinations of the ancient monastic offices of Matins and Lauds; and Vespers and Compline, respectively.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The prayer offices have an important place in Anglican history.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This nurtured a tradition of distinctive Anglican chant applied to the canticles and psalms used at the offices (although plainsong is often used as well).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In some official and many unofficial Anglican service books, these offices are supplemented by other offices such as the Little Hours of Prime and prayer during the day such as (Terce, Sext, None, and Compline).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Some Anglican monastic communities have a Daily Office based on that of the *Book of Common Prayer* but with additional antiphons and canticles, etc., for specific days of the week, specific psalms, etc.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] See, for example, Order of the Holy Cross and Order of St Helena, editors, *A Monastic Breviary* (Wilton, Conn.: Morehouse-Barlow, 1976).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] The All Saints Sisters of the Poor, with convents in Catonsville, Maryland, and elsewhere, use an elaborated version of the Anglican Daily Office.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Francis publishes *Celebrating Common Prayer*, which has become especially popular for use among Anglicans.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In addition, most prayer books include a section of prayers and devotions for family use.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the US, these offices are further supplemented by an "Order of Worship for the Evening", a prelude to or an abbreviated form of Evensong, partly derived from Orthodox prayers.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the United Kingdom, the publication of *Daily Prayer*, the third volume of *Common Worship*, was published in 2005.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] It retains the services for Morning and Evening Prayer and Compline and includes a section entitled "Prayer during the Day".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] *A New Zealand Prayer Book* of 1989 provides different outlines for Matins and Evensong on each day of the week, as well as "Midday Prayer", "Night Prayer" and "Family Prayer".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Some Anglicans who pray the office on daily basis use the present Divine Office of the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In many cities, especially in England, Anglican and Roman Catholic priests and lay people often meet several times a week to pray the office in common.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Others may privately use idiosyncratic forms borrowed from a wide range of Christian traditions.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the late medieval period, many English cathedrals and monasteries had established small choirs of trained lay clerks and boy choristers to perform polyphonic settings of the Mass in their Lady chapels.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Although these "Lady Masses" were discontinued at the Reformation, the associated musical tradition was maintained in the Elizabethan Settlement through the establishment of choral foundations for daily singing of the Divine Office by expanded choirs of men and boys.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] This resulted from an explicit addition by Elizabeth herself to the injunctions accompanying the 1559 *Book of Common Prayer* (that had itself made no mention of choral worship) by which existing choral foundations and choir schools were instructed to be continued, and their endowments secured.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Consequently, some thirty-four cathedrals, collegiate churches, and royal chapels maintained paid establishments of lay singing men and choristers in the late 16th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] All save four of these have – with interruptions during the Commonwealth and the COVID-19 pandemic – continued daily choral prayer and praise to this day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In the Offices of Morning Prayer and Evening Prayer in the 1662 *Book of Common Prayer*, these choral establishments are specified as "Quires and Places where they sing".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] For nearly three centuries, this round of daily professional choral worship represented a tradition entirely distinct from that embodied in the intoning of Parish Clerks, and the singing of "west gallery choirs" which commonly accompanied weekly worship in English parish churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In 1841, the rebuilt Leeds Parish Church established a surpliced choir to accompany parish services, drawing explicitly on the musical traditions of the ancient choral foundations.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Over the next century, the Leeds example proved immensely popular and influential for choirs in cathedrals, parish churches, and schools throughout the Anglican communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] More or less extensively adapted, this choral tradition also became the direct inspiration for robed choirs leading congregational worship in a wide range of Christian denominations.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] In 1719, the cathedral choirs of Gloucester, Hereford, and Worcester combined to establish the annual Three Choirs Festival, the precursor for the multitude of summer music festivals since.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Composers closely concerned with this tradition include Edward Elgar, Ralph Vaughan Williams, Gustav Holst, Charles Villiers Stanford, and Benjamin Britten.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] A number of important 20th-century works by non-Anglican composers were originally commissioned for the Anglican choral tradition – for example, the *Chichester Psalms* of Leonard Bernstein and the *Nunc dimittis* of Arvo Pärt.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Most Anglican Churches in the world only support marriage between a man and a woman.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p02] Some Anglican Churches allow local churches to decide about blessings of same-sex marriage, such as the Anglican Church of New Zealand, the Anglican Episcopal Church of Brazil, and the Episcopal Church (USA).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Contrary to popular misconception, the British monarch is not the constitutional "head" of the Church of England but is, in law, the church's "supreme governor", nor does the monarch have any role in provinces outside England.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The role of the crown in the Church of England is practically limited to the appointment of bishops, including the archbishop of Canterbury, and even this role is limited, as the church presents the government with a short list of candidates from which to choose.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] This process is accomplished through collaboration with and consent of ecclesial representatives *(see Ecclesiastical Commissioners)*.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Although the monarch has no constitutional role in Anglican churches in other parts of the world, the prayer books of several countries where the monarch is head of state contain prayers for him or her as sovereign.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A characteristic of Anglicanism is that it has no international juridical authority.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] All forty-two provinces of the Anglican Communion are autonomous, each with their own primate and governing structure.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] These provinces may take the form of national churches (such as in Canada, Uganda or Japan) or a collection of nations (such as the West Indies, Central Africa or South Asia), or geographical regions (such as Vanuatu and Solomon Islands) etc.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Within these provinces there may exist subdivisions, called ecclesiastical provinces, under the jurisdiction of a metropolitan archbishop.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] All provinces of the Anglican Communion consist of dioceses, each under the jurisdiction of a bishop.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the Anglican tradition, bishops must be consecrated according to the strictures of apostolic succession, which Anglicans consider one of the marks of catholicity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Apart from bishops, there are two other orders of ordained ministry: deacon and priest.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] No requirement is made for clerical celibacy, though many Anglo-Catholic priests have traditionally been bachelors.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Because of innovations that occurred at various points after the latter half of the 20th century, women may be ordained as deacons in almost all provinces, as priests in most and as bishops in many.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Anglican religious orders and communities, suppressed in England during the Reformation, have re-emerged, especially since the mid-19th century, and now have an international presence and influence.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Government in the Anglican Communion is synodical, consisting of three houses of laity (usually elected parish representatives), clergy and bishops.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] National, provincial and diocesan synods maintain different scopes of authority, depending on their canons and constitutions.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Anglicanism is not congregational in its polity: it is the diocese, not the parish church, which is the smallest unit of authority in the church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The archbishop is, therefore, recognised as the *primus inter pares* (lat.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] "first amongst equals") even though no direct authority in any province outside of England is exercised by the archbishop.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Rowan Williams, the archbishop of Canterbury from 2002 to 2012, was the first archbishop appointed from outside the Church of England since the Reformation as he was formerly the archbishop of Wales.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] On October 3, 2025, the monarch of the UK appointed Sarah Mullally as the archbishop of Canterbury making her the first woman to serve in the role and the first woman to be the "first among equals" and an "instrument of communion" within the Anglican Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] On October 16, 2025, the Chair of GAFCON, Laurent Mbanda, the Primate of Rwanda, announced that GAFCON no longer recognises the Archbishop of Canterbury as an Instrument of Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] As spiritual head of the communion, the archbishop of Canterbury maintains a certain moral authority and has the right to determine which churches will be in communion with the see.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The archbishop hosts and chairs both the Lambeth Conferences of Anglican Communion bishops and the Anglican Communion Primates' Meeting and is responsible for the invitations to them.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The archbishop also acts as the president of the secretariat of the Anglican Communion Office and its deliberative body, the Anglican Consultative Council.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Anglican Communion has no international juridical organisation.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] All international bodies are consultative and collaborative, and their resolutions are not legally binding on the autonomous provinces of the communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] There are three international bodies of note.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Like the Roman Catholic Church and the Orthodox churches, the Anglican Communion maintains the threefold ministry of deacons, presbyters (usually called "priests"), and bishops.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Bishops, who possess the fullness of Christian priesthood, are the successors of the apostles.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Primates, archbishops, and metropolitans are all bishops and members of the historical episcopate who derive their authority through apostolic succession – an unbroken line of bishops that can be traced back to the 12 apostles of Jesus.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The churches of the Anglican Communion have traditionally held that ordination in the historic episcopate is a core element in the validity of clerical ordinations.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Roman Catholic Church, however, does not recognise Anglican orders (see *Apostolicae curae*).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Some Eastern Orthodox churches have issued statements to the effect that Anglican orders could be accepted, yet have still reordained former Anglican clergy; other Eastern Orthodox churches have rejected Anglican orders altogether.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In 1922, the Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople, Meletius IV, followed by the Synod of Constantinople, issued a statement recognising Anglican Holy Orders within the Anglican Communion as valid through apostolic succession.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Following Constantinople, five other autocephalous Orthodox jurisdictions recognised the validity of Anglican Holy Orders, including Alexandria, Jerusalem, Cyprus, Greece and Romania as well as the autonomous Church of Sinai.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Bishops are assisted by priests and deacons.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Most ordained ministers in the Anglican Communion are priests, who usually work in parishes within a diocese.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Priests are in charge of the spiritual life of parishes and are usually called the rector or vicar.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A curate (or, more correctly, an "assistant curate") is a priest or deacon who assists the parish priest.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Non-parochial priests may earn their living by any vocation, although employment by educational institutions or charitable organisations is most common.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Priests also serve as chaplains of hospitals, schools, prisons, and in the armed forces.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] An archdeacon is a priest or deacon responsible for administration of an archdeaconry, which is often the name given to the principal subdivisions of a diocese.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] An archdeacon represents the diocesan bishop in his or her archdeaconry.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the Church of England, the position of archdeacon can only be held by someone in priestly orders who has been ordained for at least six years.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In some other parts of the Anglican Communion, the position can also be held by deacons.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In parts of the Anglican Communion where women cannot be ordained as priests or bishops but can be ordained as deacons, the position of archdeacon is effectively the most senior office to which an ordained woman can be appointed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A dean is a priest who is the principal cleric of a cathedral or other collegiate church and the head of the chapter of canons.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] If the cathedral or collegiate church has its own parish, the dean is usually also rector of the parish.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] However, in the Church of Ireland, the roles are often separated, and most cathedrals in the Church of England do not have associated parishes.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the Church in Wales, however, most cathedrals are parish churches and their deans are now also vicars of their parishes.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Anglican Communion recognises Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox ordinations as valid.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Outside the Anglican Communion, Anglican ordinations (at least of male priests) are recognised by the Old Catholic Church, Porvoo Communion Lutherans, and various Independent Catholic churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In Anglican churches, deacons often work directly in ministry to the marginalised inside and outside the church: the poor, the sick, the hungry, the imprisoned.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Unlike Orthodox and most Roman Catholic deacons who may be married only before ordination, deacons are permitted to marry freely both before and after ordination, as are priests.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Most deacons are preparing for priesthood and usually only remain as deacons for about a year before being ordained priests.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] However, there are some deacons who remain so.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Many provinces of the Anglican Communion ordain both men and women as deacons.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Many of those provinces that ordain women to the priesthood previously allowed them to be ordained only to the diaconate.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The effect of this was the creation of a large and overwhelmingly female diaconate for a time, as most men proceeded to be ordained priest after a short time as a deacon.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Deacons, in some dioceses, can be granted licences to solemnise matrimony, usually under the instruction of their parish priest and bishop.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] They sometimes officiate at Benediction of the Blessed Sacrament in churches which have this service.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Deacons are not permitted to preside at the Eucharist (but can lead worship with the distribution of already consecrated communion where this is permitted), absolve sins, or pronounce a blessing.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] It is the prohibition against deacons pronouncing blessings that leads some to believe that deacons cannot solemnise matrimony.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] All baptised members of the church are called Christian faithful, truly equal in dignity and in the work to build the church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Some non-ordained people also have a formal public ministry, often on a full-time and long-term basis – such as lay readers (also known as readers), churchwardens, vergers, and sextons.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Lay people also serve on the parish altar guild (preparing the altar and caring for its candles, linens, flowers, etc.), in the choir and as cantors, as ushers and greeters, and on the church council (called the "vestry" in some countries), which is the governing body of a parish.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A small yet influential aspect of Anglicanism is its religious orders and communities.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Shortly after the beginning of the Catholic Revival in the Church of England, there was a renewal of interest in re-establishing religious and monastic orders and communities.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] One of Henry VIII's earliest acts was their dissolution and seizure of their assets.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In 1841, Marian Rebecca Hughes became the first woman to take the vows of religion in communion with the Province of Canterbury since the Reformation.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In 1848, Priscilla Lydia Sellon became the superior of the Society of the Most Holy Trinity at Devonport, Plymouth, the first organised religious order.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Sellon is called "the restorer, after three centuries, of the religious life in the Church of England".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] For the next one hundred years, religious orders for both men and women proliferated throughout the world, becoming a numerically small but disproportionately influential feature of global Anglicanism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Anglican religious life at one time boasted hundreds of orders and communities, and thousands of religious.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The mixed life, combining aspects of the contemplative orders and the active orders, remains to this day a hallmark of Anglican religious life.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Another distinctive feature of Anglican religious life is the existence of some mixed-gender communities.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Since the 1960s, there has been a sharp decline in the number of professed religious in most parts of the Anglican Communion, especially in North America, Europe, and Australia.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Many once large and international communities have been reduced to a single convent or monastery with memberships of elderly men or women.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the last few decades of the 20th century, novices have for most communities been few and far between.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Some orders and communities have already become extinct.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] There are, however, still thousands of Anglican religious working today in approximately 200 communities around the world, and religious life in many parts of the Communion – especially in developing nations – flourishes.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The most significant growth has been in the Melanesian countries of the Solomon Islands, Vanuatu, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Melanesian Brotherhood, founded at Tabalia, Guadalcanal, in 1925 by Ini Kopuria, is now the largest Anglican Community in the world, with over 450 brothers in the Solomon Islands, Vanuatu, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, and the United Kingdom.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Sisters of the Church, started by Mother Emily Ayckbowm in England in 1870, has more sisters in the Solomons than all their other communities.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Community of the Sisters of Melanesia, started in 1980 by Sister Nesta Tiboe, is a growing community of women in the Solomon Islands.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Society of Saint Francis, founded as a union of various Franciscan orders in the 1920s, has experienced great growth in the Solomon Islands.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Other communities of religious have been started by Anglicans in Papua New Guinea and in Vanuatu.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Most Melanesian Anglican religious are in their early to mid-20s.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Vows may be temporary, and it is generally assumed that brothers, at least, will leave and marry in due course, making the average age 40 to 50 years younger than their brothers and sisters in other countries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Growth of religious orders, especially for women, is marked in certain parts of Africa.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] As of 2024, there are around 110 million Anglicans worldwide.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Of these, as of 2020, around 95 million are members of the Anglican Communion (excluding united churches).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] This makes the Anglican Communion the third largest Christian communion in the world, after the Roman Catholic Church and the Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The 11 provinces in Africa saw growth in the last two decades.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The ten largest member churches of the Anglican Communion, as measured by total reported membership not active membership, in 2025 were the churches based in England, Nigeria, Uganda, Kenya, Australia, South India, Southern Africa, South Sudan, Tanzania, and the Episcopal Church.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In most industrialised countries, church attendance has decreased since the 19th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Anglicanism's presence in the rest of the world is due to large-scale emigration, the establishment of expatriate communities, or the work of missionaries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Church of England has been a church of missionaries since the 17th century, when the Church first left English shores with colonists who founded what would become the United States, Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and South Africa, and established Anglican churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] For example, an Anglican chaplain, Robert Wolfall, with Martin Frobisher's Arctic expedition, celebrated the Eucharist in 1578 in Frobisher Bay.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The first Anglican church in the Americas was built at Jamestown, Virginia, in 1607.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] By the 18th century, missionaries worked to establish Anglican churches in Asia, Africa, and Latin America.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The great Church of England missionary societies were founded; for example, the Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge (SPCK) in 1698, the Society for the Propagation of the Gospel in Foreign Parts (SPG) in 1701, and the Church Mission Society (CMS) in 1799.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the 20th century, the Church of England developed new forms of evangelism, including the Alpha course in 1990, which was developed and propagated from Holy Trinity Brompton Church in London.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the 21st century, there has been renewed effort to reach children and youth.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] For those who prefer not to actually visit a brick and mortar church, there are Internet ministries, such as the Diocese of Oxford's online Anglican i-Church, which was founded on the web in 2005.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Anglican interest in ecumenical dialogue can be traced back to the time of the Reformation and dialogues with both Orthodox and Lutheran churches in the 16th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the 19th century, with the rise of the Oxford Movement, there arose greater concern for reunion of the churches of "Catholic confession".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] This desire to work towards full communion with other denominations led to the development of the Chicago-Lambeth Quadrilateral, approved by the third Lambeth Conference of 1888.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The four points (the sufficiency of scripture, the historic creeds, the two dominical sacraments, and the historic episcopate) were proposed as a basis for discussion, although they have frequently been taken as a non-negotiable bottom-line for any form of reunion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Anglicanism in general has always sought a balance between the emphases of Catholicism and Protestantism, while tolerating a range of expressions of evangelicalism and ceremony.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Clergy and laity from all Anglican churchmanship traditions have been active in the formation of the Continuing movement.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] While there are high church, broad-church and low-church Continuing Anglicans, many Continuing churches are Anglo-Catholic with highly ceremonial liturgical practices.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Others belong to a more evangelical or low-church tradition and tend to support the Thirty-nine Articles and simpler worship services.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Morning Prayer, for instance, is often used instead of the Holy Eucharist for Sunday worship services, although this is not necessarily true of all low-church parishes.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Most Continuing churches in the United States reject the 1979 revision of the *Book of Common Prayer* by the Episcopal Church and use the 1928 version for their services instead.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In addition, Anglo-Catholic bodies may use the Anglican Missal, Anglican Service Book or English Missal when celebrating Mass.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A changing focus on social issues after the World War II led to Lambeth Conference resolutions countenancing contraception and the remarriage of divorced persons.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Eventually, most provinces approved the ordination of women.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In more recent years, some jurisdictions have permitted the ordination of people in same-sex relationships and authorised rites for the blessing of same-sex unions (see Homosexuality and Anglicanism).
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] "The more liberal provinces that are open to changing Church doctrine on marriage in order to allow for same-sex unions include Brazil, Canada, New Zealand, Scotland, South India, South Africa, the US and Wales", while the more conservative provinces are primarily located in the Global South.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The lack of social consensus among and within provinces of diverse cultural traditions has resulted in considerable conflict and even schism concerning some or all of these developments, as was the case in the Anglican realignment.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Others have, at various times, joined the Continuing Anglican movement or departed for non-Anglican evangelical churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The term "Continuing Anglicanism" refers to a number of church bodies which have formed outside of the Anglican Communion in the belief that traditional forms of Anglican faith, worship, and order have been unacceptably revised or abandoned within some Anglican Communion churches in recent decades.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] They therefore claim that they are "continuing" traditional Anglicanism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The modern Continuing Anglican movement principally dates to the Congress of St.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Louis, held in the United States in 1977, where participants rejected changes that had been made in the Episcopal Church's *Book of Common Prayer* and also the Episcopal Church's approval of the ordination of women to the priesthood.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] More recent changes in the North American churches of the Anglican Communion, such as the introduction of same-sex marriage rites and the ordination of gay and lesbian people to the priesthood and episcopate, have created further separations.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Continuing churches have generally been formed by people who have left the Anglican Communion.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The original Anglican churches are charged by the Continuing Anglicans with being greatly compromised by secular cultural standards and liberal theology.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Many Continuing Anglicans believe that the faith of some churches in communion with the archbishop of Canterbury has become unorthodox and therefore have not sought to also be in communion with him.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The original continuing parishes in the United States were found mainly in metropolitan areas.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Since the late 1990s, a number have appeared in smaller communities, often as a result of a division in the town's existing Episcopal churches.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A concern for social justice can be traced to very early Anglican beliefs, relating to an intertwined theology of God, nature, and humanity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Lord Shaftesbury, a devout evangelical, campaigned to improve the conditions in factories, in mines, for chimney sweeps, and for the education of the very poor.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] For years, he was chairman of the Ragged School Board.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Frederick Denison Maurice was a leading figure advocating reform, founding so-called "producer's co-operatives" and the Working Men's College.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] A question of whether or not Christianity is a pacifist religion has remained a matter of debate for Anglicans.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The leading Anglican spokesman for pacifist ideas, from 1914 to 1945, was Ernest Barnes, bishop of Birmingham from 1924 to 1953.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In 1937, the Anglican Pacifist Fellowship emerged as a distinct reform organisation, seeking to make pacifism a clearly defined part of Anglican theology.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The group rapidly gained popularity amongst Anglican intellectuals, including Vera Brittain, Evelyn Underhill, and the former British political leader George Lansbury.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Furthermore, Dick Sheppard, who during the 1930s was one of Britain's most famous Anglican priests due to his landmark sermon broadcasts for BBC Radio, founded the Peace Pledge Union, a secular pacifist organisation for the non-religious that gained considerable support throughout the 1930s.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Whilst never actively endorsed by Anglican churches, many Anglicans unofficially have adopted the Augustinian "Just War" doctrine.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The Anglican Pacifist Fellowship remains highly active throughout the Anglican world.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] It rejects this doctrine of "just war" and seeks to reform the Church by reintroducing the pacifism inherent in the beliefs of many of the earliest Christians and present in their interpretation of Christ's Sermon on the Mount.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The focus on other social issues became increasingly diffuse after World War II.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] The growing independence and strength of Anglican churches in the Global South brought new emphasis to issues of global poverty, the inequitable distribution of resources, and the lingering effects of colonialism.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In this regard, figures such as Desmond Tutu and Ted Scott were instrumental in mobilising Anglicans worldwide against the apartheid policies of South Africa.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] While individual Anglicans and member churches within the Communion differ in practice over the circumstances in which abortion should or should not be permitted, Lambeth Conference resolutions have consistently held to a conservative view on the issue.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] In the context of debates around and proposals for the legalisation of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the 1998 Conference affirmed that "life is God-given and has intrinsic sanctity, significance and worth".
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] On 4 November 2009, Pope Benedict XVI issued an apostolic constitution, *Anglicanorum Coetibus*, to allow groups of former Anglicans to enter into full communion with the Roman Catholic Church as members of personal ordinariates.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] Pope Benedict XVI approved, within the apostolic constitution, a canonical structure that provides for personal ordinariates which will allow former Anglicans to enter full communion with the Roman Catholic Church while preserving elements of distinctive Anglican spiritual patrimony.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] For each personal ordinariate, the ordinary may be a former Anglican bishop or priest.
[src:august-bank-holiday/anglican-p03] It was expected that provision would be made to allow the retention of aspects of Anglican liturgy.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] The **August Bank Holiday** or **Summer Bank Holiday** is a public holiday in the United Kingdom, part of the statutory bank holiday provision.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] Originally, the holiday was held on the first Monday of August across the country, but was changed in the late 1960s to the last Monday in August for England, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] It remains the first Monday for Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] The holiday was one of four created by the Bank Holidays Act 1871 (along with Easter Monday, Whit Monday and Boxing Day), being the only one which was not linked to an Anglican religious festival.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] The act was introduced by Liberal politician Sir John Lubbock.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] Lubbock argued that the act was passed with relative ease because of the naming as a 'bank' holiday, with those who might have opposed it thinking it only applied to banks.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] In 1964, an experimental move to the end of August was announced by the Secretary of State for Industry, Trade and Regional Development, Edward Heath, taking effect for two years from 1965, responding to pressure from the holiday industry to extend the season.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] The move applied to England and Wales, but not to Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] There was consultation on other methods of staggering holidays and reducing congestion related to this.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] Other suggestions included staggering school holidays by region, and introducing a four-term school year.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] Following the two year trial, each year's date was announced in Parliament on an *ad hoc* basis, causing problems for publishers of the calendars and diaries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] The rule seems to have been to select the weekend of the last Saturday in August, so that in 1968 and 1969 Bank Holiday Monday actually fell in September, causing concern amongst some politicians.
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] The date was settled in statute with the passage of the Banking and Financial Dealings Act 1971, which remains in force today, with the date specified as "the last Monday in August".
[src:august-bank-holiday/august-bank-holiday] In 2014, a Private member's bill was introduced by Conservative MP Peter Bone to rename the holiday as *Margaret Thatcher* day, in honour of the late Prime Minister, but the bill failed to progress past the first reading.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holiday] A **bank holiday** is a national public holiday in the United Kingdom and the Crown Dependencies, and a colloquial term for a public holiday in Ireland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holiday] In the United Kingdom, the term is used to refer to all public holidays, be they set out in statute, declared by royal proclamation, or held by convention under common law.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holiday] In Ireland, there are some bank holidays which are not public holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holiday] The term "bank holiday" refers to the fact that banking institutions typically close for business on such holidays, as they once did on certain saint's days.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holidays-act-1871] 17) established public holidays (known as bank holidays) in addition to those customarily recognised in the United Kingdom.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holidays-act-1871] In England, Wales and Ireland, Good Friday and Christmas Day were considered traditional days of rest (as were Sundays) and therefore it was felt unnecessary to include them in the Act; especially as the Act extended the existing law relating to those days to the new bank holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holidays-act-1871] The Bank Holidays Act was introduced by John Lubbock, 1st Baron Avebury who originally proposed four bank holidays in England and Wales (Easter Monday, the first Monday in August, Whit Monday, and Boxing Day) and five in Scotland, which had a slightly different cultural calendar.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holidays-act-1871] They were added to the traditional religious holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holidays-act-1871] Some people even nicknamed these new holidays “St Lubbock’s Days”.
[src:august-bank-holiday/bank-holidays-act-1871] The Act was repealed in 1971 and superseded by the Banking and Financial Dealings Act 1971, which remains in force.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In the United Kingdom, public holidays are days on which most businesses and non-essential services are closed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Many retail businesses (especially the larger ones) do open on some of the public holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] There are restrictions on trading on Sundays, Easter and Christmas Day in England and Wales and on New Year's Day and Christmas Day in Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Public holidays defined by statute are called "bank holidays", but this term can also be used to include common law holidays, which are held by convention.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The term "public holidays" can refer exclusively to common law holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] There is no automatic right to paid time off on these days, or any right to a holiday at all, but banks close and the majority of the working population is granted time off work or extra pay for working on these days, depending on their contracts.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Before 1980, collective agreements widely included public holidays as part of a standard entitlement to time off.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Schedule 11 of the Employment Protection Act 1975 enabled mandatory extension of collective agreements across sectors, but this was repealed with effect from 1980, and the Fair Wages Resolution 1946 (affecting public sector contracts) was repealed with effect from 1983.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] This meant there was no effective legal mechanism for holidays until the Working Time Regulations 1998, based on the Working Time Directive restored 20 and then 28 days paid holidays - however employers do not need to grant paid holidays on public holiday days.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] There are eight bank holidays a year in England and Wales, nine in Scotland and ten in Northern Ireland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Additional days have been allocated for special events, such as royal weddings, coronations, and jubilees.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] There are seven bank holidays common to all jurisdictions: New Year's Day, Good Friday, the early May bank holiday (May Day), the Spring bank holiday, the Summer bank holiday, Christmas Day, and Boxing Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Easter Monday is a bank holiday in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland, but not in Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In Northern Ireland, Saint Patrick's Day and Orangemen's Day are also bank holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In Scotland, 2 January and St Andrew's Day are bank holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The Summer bank holiday varies according to jurisdiction: in Scotland, it is on the first Monday in August, and in the rest of the United Kingdom, it is on the last Monday in August.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In England, Wales and Northern Ireland, Good Friday and Christmas Day are common law holidays, having been customary holidays since time immemorial.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The first official bank holidays were named in the Bank Holidays Act 1871, introduced by Liberal politician and banker Sir John Lubbock.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Under the Act, "no person was compelled to make any payment or to do any act upon a bank holiday which he would not be compelled to do or make on Christmas Day or Good Friday, and the making of a payment or the doing of an act on the following day was equivalent to doing it on the holiday".
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] People were so grateful that some called the first bank holidays *St Lubbock's Days* for a while.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The Act did not include Good Friday and Christmas Day as bank holidays in England, Wales, or Ireland because they were already recognised as common law holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In 1903, the Bank Holiday (Ireland) Act added 17 March, Saint Patrick's Day, as a bank holiday in Ireland only.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] New Year's Day did not become a bank holiday in England, Wales and Northern Ireland until 1 January 1974.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Boxing Day did not become a bank holiday in Scotland until 1974.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Starting in 1965, experimentally, the August Bank Holiday weekend was observed at the end of August "to give a lead in extending British holidays over a longer summer period".
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Each year's date was announced in Parliament on an *ad hoc* basis, to the despair of the calendar and diary publishing trade.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The rule seems to have been to select the weekend of the last Saturday in August, so that in 1968 and 1969 Bank Holiday Monday actually fell in September.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] A century after the 1871 act, the **Banking and Financial Dealings Act 1971** (c.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] 80), which currently regulates bank holidays in the UK, was passed.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The majority of the current bank holidays were specified in the 1971 Act: however New Year's Day and May Day were not introduced throughout the whole of the UK until 1974 and 1978 respectively.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The date of the August bank holiday was changed from the first Monday in August to the last Monday in August in England, Wales and Northern Ireland (but not in Scotland), and the Whitsun bank holiday (Whit Monday) was replaced by the Late Spring Bank Holiday, fixed as the last Monday in May.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] From 1978, the final Monday of May in Scotland (a statutory holiday in the rest of the UK) and the first Monday in May in the rest of the UK (a statutory holiday in Scotland) have been proclaimed as bank holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In January 2007, the St Andrew's Day Bank Holiday (Scotland) Act 2007 was given royal assent, making 30 November (or the following Monday if 30 November falls on a weekend) a bank holiday in Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] There are calls for extra public holidays on the patron saints' days in England (for St.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] For example, in 2018 the Labour Party announced it would make those days bank holidays if elected.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The same year, an online petition to the Prime Minister as to Wales received 3,577 signatures.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In 2009, it was reported that St Piran's Day (patron saint of Cornwall) on 5 March is already given as an unofficial day off to many government and other workers in the county.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] It is suggested that a move from the May bank holiday to a St Piran's Day bank holiday in Cornwall would benefit the Cornish economy by £20–35 million.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The number of holidays in the UK is relatively small compared to many other European countries.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] However, direct comparison is inaccurate since the 'substitute day' scheme of deferment does not apply in most European countries, where holidays that coincide with a weekend (29% of fixed-date holidays) are "lost".
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In fact, the average number of non-weekend holidays in such countries is only marginally higher (and in some cases lower) than the UK.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Worth mentioning is that public holidays in Europe which fall on Thursday or Tuesday typically become "puente" or "bridge" four-day or even six-day extended holiday weekends as people tend to use one or two days from their holiday entitlement to take off Monday and/or Friday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Royal proclamation is also used to move bank holidays that would otherwise fall on a weekend and to create extra one-off bank holidays for special occasions.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The Act does not provide for a bank holiday to be suppressed by royal proclamation without appointing another day in its place.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In this way, public holidays are not "lost" in years when they coincide with weekends.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] These deferred bank holiday days are termed a "bank holiday in lieu" of the typical anniversary date.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] In the legislation they are known as "substitute days".
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The movement of the St Andrew's Day Scottish holiday to the nearest Monday when 30 November is a weekend day is statutory and does not require a proclamation.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Bank holidays falling on a weekend are always moved to a later date, not an earlier one.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Although there is no statutory right for workers to take paid leave on bank holidays, where paid leave is given (either because the business is closed or for other reasons), the bank holiday can count towards the minimum statutory holiday entitlement.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Likewise, if people are required to work on a bank holiday, there is no statutory right to an enhanced pay rate nor to a day off *in lieu*, although many employers do give either or both.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Any rights in this respect depend on the person's contract of employment.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] The statutory minimum paid holidays is 28 days (or 5.6 weeks) a year under the Working Time Regulations 1998 (including any bank holidays or public holidays that are taken).
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Local holidays are determined by local authorities across Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Some of these may be taken in lieu of statutory holidays while others may be additional holidays, although many companies, including Royal Mail, do not follow all the holidays listed below, and many swap between English and local holidays.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Since Easter 1996 the Scottish clearing banks have harmonised the days on which they are closed with those in England and Wales and are therefore closed on Easter Monday and the last Monday in August (rather than the first).
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] This has resulted in a number of local authorities creating a public holiday on Easter Monday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] Previously Easter Monday had not been a public holiday in Scotland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] There have been protests about banks opening on 2 January since this decision was taken.
[src:august-bank-holiday/banking-and-financial-dealings-act-1971] This has resulted in many banks now providing only a limited service on 2 January, with most members of staff still entitled to the holiday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] While the holiday's roots can be traced back to Britain, where Boxing Day is also known as St.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Stephen's Day, the origin of the term itself is not definitive.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The European tradition of giving money and other gifts to those in need, or in service positions, has been dated to the Middle Ages, but the exact origin is unknown; it may refer to the alms box placed in the narthex of Christian churches to collect donations for the poor.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] On this day, it is customary in some localities for the alms boxes to be opened and distributed to the poor.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In Britain, it was a custom for tradesmen to collect "Christmas boxes" of money or presents on the first weekday after Christmas as thanks for good service throughout the year.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This is mentioned in Samuel Pepys' diary entry for 19 December 1663.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This custom is linked to an older British tradition in which the servants of the wealthy were allowed the next day to visit their families since they would have had to serve their masters on Christmas Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The employers would give each servant a box to take home containing gifts, bonuses, and sometimes leftover food.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Seasonal gratuities to local service workers became an established practice in Britain by the 18th century.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Saint Stephen's Day, a religious holiday, also falls on 26 December.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In the United Kingdom, Boxing Day could not fall on Sunday 26 December.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Instead, Boxing Day would be celebrated on Monday 27 December, with the preceding Sunday called Christmas Sunday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This rule was independent of the rule of bank holidays being taken in lieu.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Over time Sunday 26 December increasingly became referred to as Boxing Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Unlike the contemporary understanding of Boxing Day itself, the associated bank holiday or public holiday always falls on a weekday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] When 25 December falls on a Saturday and 26 December falls on a Sunday, the Christmas Day substitute holiday is observed on Monday 27 December, with the Boxing Day substitute holiday observed on Tuesday 28 December.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] When Christmas Day is a Sunday, the Boxing Day holiday is still observed on Monday 26 December, with the substitute holiday for Christmas Day observed on Tuesday 27 December.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and Trinidad and Tobago, Boxing Day is a popular shopping holiday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Boxing Day sales are common, and shops often allow dramatic price reductions.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] For many merchants, Boxing Day has become the day of the year with the greatest revenue.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In the UK, it was estimated in 2009 that up to 12 million shoppers appeared at the sales (a rise of almost 20% compared to 2008, although this was also affected by the fact that the VAT was about to revert to 17.5% from 1 January, following the temporary reduction to 15%).
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Many retailers open very early (typically 5 am or even earlier) and offer doorbuster deals and loss leaders to draw people to their stores.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] It is not uncommon for long queues to form early in the morning of 26 December, hours before the opening of shops holding the big sales, especially at big-box consumer electronics retailers.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Many stores have a limited quantity of big draw or deeply discounted items.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Because of the shoulder-to-shoulder crowds, many choose to stay at home and avoid the hectic shopping experience.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Local media often covers the event, mentioning how early the shoppers began queuing up and showing videos of shoppers queuing and later leaving with their purchased items.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Many retailers have implemented practices aimed at managing large numbers of shoppers.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] They may limit entrances, restrict the number of patrons in a store at a time, provide tickets to people at the head of the queue to guarantee them a hot ticket item, or canvass queued-up shoppers to inform them of inventory limitations.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In Canada, Boxing Day was historically the largest retail shopping day of the year, particularly before the widespread adoption of Black Friday sales in the 2010s.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Major retailers traditionally offered deep post-Christmas discounts, and large crowds were common in shopping centres across the country.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In some areas of Canada, particularly in Atlantic Canada and parts of Northern Ontario, most retailers are prohibited from opening on Boxing Day, either by provincial law or by municipal bylaw, or by informal agreement among major retailers, to provide a day of relaxation following Christmas Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In these areas, sales otherwise scheduled for 26 December are moved to the 27th.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The city council of Greater Sudbury, Ontario, which was the largest city in Canada to maintain this restriction as of the early 2010s, formally repealed its store hours bylaw on 9 December 2014.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] While Boxing Day is 26 December, many retailers run the sales for several days before or after 26 December, often up to New Year's Eve, branding it as "Boxing Week".
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Notably, in the recession of late 2008, a record number of retailers held early promotions because of the weak economy.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In 2009, many retailers with both online and High Street stores launched their online sales on Christmas Eve and their High Street sales on Boxing Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In terms of seasonal or holiday shopping traditions, Boxing Day sales have been compared to the US phenomenon of Black Friday sales – Black Friday being the Friday following the American Thanksgiving holiday in late November.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In the late 2000s, when the Canadian and United States dollars were near parity, many Canadian retailers began to hold Black Friday promotions in an effort to discourage shoppers from crossing the border to visit United States stores.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This may have been a contributory factor, since 2013, in a relative decline of traditional Canadian Boxing Day sales, when compared with sales on Black Friday.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The traditional Boxing Day sales in the United Kingdom were never as large an event as the Black Friday sales are in the United States.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] However, many British retailers began to see an opportunity to import the Black Friday tradition into the UK, not to replace Boxing Day sales, but as an addition to their overall seasonal promotions.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] However, Black Friday and Boxing Day are close enough together that spending on one sale was likely to affect spending on the other.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Ultimately, the result was a marked decline in traditional Boxing Day sales in the UK.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The change was initially facilitated, although not necessarily by design, by U.S.-owned retailers such as Amazon, and Asda (then a subsidiary of US-based Walmart).
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This phenomenon was furthered by a general decline in traditional high-street shopping and a growing online marketplace, which is more international by nature.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This led, in 2015, to greater November retail sales in the UK than in December for the first time.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Boxing Day sales are not a prominent tradition in the United States, although many retailers often begin after-Christmas sales that day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] It is typically the earliest starting day after Christmas for people to return unwanted gifts for exchanges or refunds and to redeem gift cards.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Starting in the mid-2020s, American retailers began promoting their after-Christmas sales as “Boxing Day” or “Boxing Week” sales.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In the United Kingdom, it is traditional for the Home Nations' major football leagues (including, most prominently, the Premier League, Scottish Premiership, and NIFL Premiership) to hold a full programme of fixtures on Boxing Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Originally, matches on Boxing Day were played against local rivals so that teams and their fans would not have to travel long distances to away games on the day after Christmas.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The 2022 Premier League Boxing Day fixtures saw the return of domestic top flight football for the 2022–23 Premier League season, following the six-week break for the 2022 FIFA World Cup.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In rugby league, festive fixtures were a staple of the traditional winter season.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Since the transition to a summer season in the 1990s, no formal fixtures are now arranged on Boxing Day but some clubs, such as Wakefield Trinity, arrange a traditional local derby friendly fixture instead.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Since 1980, the Australian cricket team has traditionally opened one of the test matches of its summer season on Boxing Day at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] While several test matches had occasionally been held at the MCG around Boxing Day, it was not until 1980 that the concept was formalized by the Australian Cricket Board.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race is also traditionally held on Boxing Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In horse racing, there is the King George VI Chase at Kempton Park Racecourse in Surrey, England.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] It is the second most prestigious chase in Britain, after the Cheltenham Gold Cup.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In addition to the prestigious race at Kempton, in Britain, it is usually the day with the most racing meetings of the year, with eight in 2016, in addition to three more in Ireland.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In Barbados, the final day of horse racing is held on Boxing Day at The Historic Garrison Savannah, a UNESCO world heritage site.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This tradition has been going on for decades in this former British colony.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Boxing Day is one of the main days in the hunting calendar for hunts in the UK and US, with most hunts (both mounted foxhound or harrier packs and foot packs of beagles or bassets) holding meets, often in town or village centres.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] Several ice hockey contests are associated with the day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The IIHF World Junior Championship typically begins on 26 December, while the Spengler Cup also begins on 23 December in Davos, Switzerland; the Spengler Cup competition includes HC Davos, Team Canada, and other top European hockey teams.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] The National Hockey League traditionally had close to a full slate of games (10 were played in 2011), following the league-wide days off given for Christmas Eve and Christmas Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In Sweden, the related sport of bandy is also associated with the day, with Saint Stephen's Day bandy games having become an established tradition.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In some African Commonwealth nations, particularly Ghana, Uganda, Malawi, Zambia, and Tanzania, professional boxing contests are held on Boxing Day.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] This practice has also been followed for decades in Guyana and Italy.
[src:august-bank-holiday/boxing-day] In the UK it is common to eat leftovers from the previous day's Christmas dinner, with turkey often being used in a Boxing Day sandwich or curry.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Ancient documents and inscriptions, such as those from Rome and China, include early forms of calendars.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Printing gave rise to many related types of publication which track dates, of which calendars are just one.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] The introduction of broadside printing allowed a calendar to be printed on a single large sheet of paper, differentiating the basic calendar from more detailed diaries and practica.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] In the absence of accurate clocks, calendars doubled as timekeeping aids - by noting the times of sunrise and moonrise, calendars helped farmers tell the time while in the fields.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Alongside their practical use, calendars have developed into a decorative item.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Typically, each page will include a new image, which may be related to the season.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Common subjects include landscapes, automobiles, wildlife, male or female models and popular culture.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Businesses frequently give wall calendars branded with their names and contact information away for free to customers as promotional merchandise.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] An especially influential type of calendar is the nude calendar or pin-up calendar - a calendar containing images of either scantily-clad or naked models.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] Some are essentially pornographic in nature, but a more recent evolution is calendars featuring people in comic situations and published for charity.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] A popular subgenre of pin-up calendar is the firefighter calendar.
[src:august-bank-holiday/calendar-stationery] There are many types of calendar, serving a wide variety of uses.
